4. Frontend Source Code

The frontend was developed using EJS, Bootstrap, HTML, CSS, and JavaScript. It provides users with an interactive and responsive interface for managing financial information. Bootstrap classes were used throughout the interface to maintain responsive layouts across desktop, tablet, and mobile devices.

The frontend implementation includes:
- Dashboard Pages
- Authentication Pages
- Transaction Forms
- Wallet Management Screens
- Budget Management Pages
- Reminder Management Interfaces
- Analytics and Reporting Views
- Settings and Profile Pages

1. Dashboard Pages
Sample EJS + Bootstrap code for summary cards:

```ejs
<div class="row g-3">
  <div class="col-md-4">
    <div class="card shadow-sm border-0">
      <div class="card-body">
        <h6 class="text-muted">Total Income</h6>
        <h3 class="text-success">Rs. <%= totalIncome %></h3>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="col-md-4">
    <div class="card shadow-sm border-0">
      <div class="card-body">
        <h6 class="text-muted">Total Expense</h6>
        <h3 class="text-danger">Rs. <%= totalExpense %></h3>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="col-md-4">
    <div class="card shadow-sm border-0">
      <div class="card-body">
        <h6 class="text-muted">Balance</h6>
        <h3 class="text-primary">Rs. <%= balance %></h3>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
```

2. Authentication Pages
Sample login page with OTP/email input:

```ejs
<form action="/" method="POST" class="card p-4 shadow-sm">
  <h3 class="mb-3">Sign In</h3>
  <label class="form-label">Email Address</label>
  <input type="email" name="email" class="form-control mb-3" placeholder="Enter your email" required>
  <button type="submit" class="btn btn-primary w-100">Request OTP</button>
</form>
```

3. Transaction Forms
Sample transaction entry form:

```ejs
<form action="/transactions/add" method="POST" class="row g-3">
  <div class="col-md-6">
    <label class="form-label">Title</label>
    <input type="text" name="title" class="form-control" required>
  </div>
  <div class="col-md-3">
    <label class="form-label">Amount</label>
    <input type="number" name="amount" class="form-control" required>
  </div>
  <div class="col-md-3">
    <label class="form-label">Type</label>
    <select name="type" class="form-select">
      <option value="income">Income</option>
      <option value="expense">Expense</option>
    </select>
  </div>
  <div class="col-12">
    <button type="submit" class="btn btn-success">Save Transaction</button>
  </div>
</form>
```

4. Wallet Management Screens
Sample wallet card layout:

```ejs
<div class="row g-3">
  <% wallets.forEach(wallet => { %>
    <div class="col-md-4">
      <div class="card border-0 shadow-sm">
        <div class="card-body">
          <h5><%= wallet.name %></h5>
          <p class="mb-0 text-muted">Balance</p>
          <h4 class="text-primary">Rs. <%= wallet.balance %></h4>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  <% }) %>
</div>
```

5. Budget Management Pages
Sample budget progress section:

```ejs
<div class="card p-3 shadow-sm">
  <h5>Monthly Budget</h5>
  <p>Target: Rs. <%= budget.target %></p>
  <div class="progress" style="height: 10px;">
    <div class="progress-bar bg-warning" style="width: <%= budget.usedPercent %>%"></div>
  </div>
  <small class="text-muted"><%= budget.usedPercent %>% used</small>
</div>
```

6. Reminder Management Interfaces
Sample reminder list:

```ejs
<table class="table table-bordered align-middle">
  <thead>
    <tr>
      <th>Title</th>
      <th>Date</th>
      <th>Status</th>
    </tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <% reminders.forEach(reminder => { %>
      <tr>
        <td><%= reminder.title %></td>
        <td><%= reminder.date %></td>
        <td><span class="badge bg-info"><%= reminder.status %></span></td>
      </tr>
    <% }) %>
  </tbody>
</table>
```

7. Analytics and Reporting Views
Sample chart container for reports:

```ejs
<div class="card shadow-sm">
  <div class="card-body">
    <h5 class="mb-3">Expense Analytics</h5>
    <canvas id="expenseChart"></canvas>
  </div>
</div>

<script>
  const chartLabels = <%- JSON.stringify(monthLabels) %>;
  const chartValues = <%- JSON.stringify(monthExpense) %>;
</script>
```

8. Settings and Profile Pages
Sample profile update form:

```ejs
<form action="/profile/update" method="POST" class="card p-4 shadow-sm">
  <div class="mb-3">
    <label class="form-label">Full Name</label>
    <input type="text" name="name" value="<%= user.name %>" class="form-control">
  </div>
  <div class="mb-3">
    <label class="form-label">Email</label>
    <input type="email" name="email" value="<%= user.email %>" class="form-control">
  </div>
  <button type="submit" class="btn btn-primary">Update Profile</button>
</form>
```

9. CSS and JavaScript Usage
Sample custom CSS and JavaScript used to improve UI behavior:

```html
<style>
  .summary-card {
    border-radius: 12px;
    transition: transform 0.2s ease;
  }

  .summary-card:hover {
    transform: translateY(-4px);
  }
</style>

<script>
  document.querySelectorAll(".auto-close-alert").forEach((alertBox) => {
    setTimeout(() => alertBox.remove(), 3000);
  });
</script>
```

Conclusion:
The frontend of the Expense Tracker project was built with EJS templates, Bootstrap responsive components, standard HTML structure, custom CSS styling, and JavaScript for dynamic behavior. This combination helped create a user-friendly and responsive application interface for all core modules of the system.
